'''Ganges Island''', a [[phantom island]] known as {{nihongo||中ノ鳥島|Nakanotorishima|literally "central bird island"}} in Japanese, appeared at {{coord|30|45|N|154|25|E|type:isle|display=inline}} on maps of the late 19th and early 20th centuries.<ref>{{cite book | last = Stommel | first = Henry | title = Lost Islands: The Story of Islands That Have Vanished from Nautical Charts | publisher = University of British Columbia Press | location = Vancouver | year = 1984 | isbn = 0-7748-0210-3 | pages = xvii, 132 }}</ref> Reports of its disappearance appeared in 1933.<ref>[http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Article/straitstimes19330712-1.2.100.aspx "Island in Pacific Vanishes".] ''[[The Straits Times]]''. 12 July 1933. p. 12.</ref>
The purported island was considered a part of an [[Anson Archipelago]], which included other phantom islands such as [[Los Jardines]] as well as real islands such as [[Wake Island|Wake]] and [[Marcus Island]]s.
{{Gallery |title=Maps showing Ganges Island |width=250 |height=200 |lines=4 |align=center |File:1855 Spruner Map of Australia and Polynesia with an overview of Discoveries and Colonization - Geographicus - AustraliaPolynesia-spruner-1855.jpg|An 1855 German map showing Ganges Island east of the [[Bonin Islands]] ("Munin-Sima") |File:Stielers_Handatlas_1891_75.jpg|An 1891 German map showing Ganges Island in the [[Anson Archipelago]], east of the Bonin Islands |File:LA2-Blitz-0298.jpg|An 1932 German map showing Ganges Island east of the Bonin Islands }}
==See also== *[[Minamitorishima]], literally "southern bird island" *[[Okinotorishima]], literally "distant bird island"
