[[Image:Guadeloupe2007.png|thumb|320px|In green (with red legend) are the constituent parts of the Guadeloupe ''région/département'' among the [[Leeward Islands]]. The 2 islands of Guadeloupe proper are: [[Basse-Terre Island]] (''left'') and [[Grande-Terre]] (''right)''.]]
The department of '''[[Guadeloupe]]''' comprises five [[island]]s: Guadeloupe island composed of [[Basse-Terre Island]] and [[Grande-Terre]] (separated from Basse-Terre by a narrow sea channel called salt river) and the [[Dependencies of Guadeloupe|dependencies]] composed by the adjacent French islands of [[La Désirade]], [[Les Saintes]] and [[Marie-Galante]]. Basse-Terre has a rough [[volcanic]] relief whilst/while Grande-Terre features rolling hills and flat plains. Guadeloupe was formed from multiple volcanoes, of which only Basse-Terre is not extinct.<ref>[http://www.ipgp.jussieu.fr/~beaudu/download/2004_Komorowski_VHA.pdf]</ref>
Further to the north, [[Saint-Barthélemy]] and the French part of [[Saint Martin]] come under the jurisdiction of Guadeloupe. On December 7, 2003, both of these areas voted to become an overseas territorial collectivity.<ref>[http://www.statoids.com/ugp.html]</ref> <!-- == Climate == {{Weather box |location = Basse-Terre—capital of Guadeloupe |metric first = yes |single line = yes |Jan high C = 28 |Feb high C = 28 |Mar high C = 28 |Apr high C = 29 |May high C = 30 |Jun high C = 31 |Jul high C = 33 |Aug high C = 31 |Sep high C = 31 |Oct high C = 30 |Nov high C = 29 |Dec high C = 29 |year high C = 30 |Jan mean C = 24 |Feb mean C = 24 |Mar mean C = 25 |Apr mean C = 26 |May mean C = 27 |Jun mean C = 27 |Jul mean C = 29 |Aug mean C = 27 |Sep mean C = 27 |Oct mean C = 27 |Nov mean C = 26 |Dec mean C = 25 |year mean C = 26 |Jan low C = 20 |Feb low C = 20 |Mar low C = 21 |Apr low C = 22 |May low C = 23 |Jun low C = 24 |Jul low C = 25 |Aug low C = 23 |Sep low C = 23 |Oct low C = 23 |Nov low C = 22 |Dec low C = 21 |year low C = 22 |Jan precipitation cm = 8 |Feb precipitation cm = 6 |Mar precipitation cm = 7 |Apr precipitation cm = 11 |May precipitation cm = 15 |Jun precipitation cm = 12 |Jul precipitation cm = 16 |Aug precipitation cm = 19 |Sep precipitation cm = 23 |Oct precipitation cm = 22 |Nov precipitation cm = 22 |Dec precipitation cm = 14 |year precipitation cm = 178 |source 1 = Weatherbase<ref name="Weatherbase">{{cite web |url=http://www.weatherbase.com/weather/weatherall.php3?s=79887&refer=&units=metric |title=Weatherbase: Historical Weather for Basse-Terre |accessdate=}}</ref> |date=August 2010 }} --> == Hurricanes == [[Image:Guadeloupe map.png|thumb|300px|right|Map of the Guadeloupe archipelago]] [[File:Guadeloupe department relief location map.jpg|thumb|300px|right|Topography]] [[File:La Désirade.JPG|thumb|View of La Désirade from [[Pointe des Châteaux (Guadeloupe)|Pointe des Châteaux]], the easternmost part of Grande-Terre.]]
The department was devastated by several hurricanes in modern times: * On 12 September, [[1928 Okeechobee hurricane]] caused extensive damage and killed thousands of people. * On 22 August 1964, Guadeloupe was ravaged by [[Hurricane Cleo]], which killed 14 people. * Two years later, on 27 September 1966, [[Hurricane Inez]] caused extensive damage and killed 27 people, mostly in Grande-Terre. [[Charles De Gaulle]] visited the island after the hurricanes and declared it a disaster area. * On 17 September 1989, [[Saffir–Simpson Hurricane Scale|Category 4]] [[Hurricane Hugo]] caused very extensive damage, left more than 35,000 homeless, destroyed 10,000 homes, 100 percent of the banana crops, and 60 percent of the sugar cane crops. * From late August to mid September 1995, the island was in the path of three successive cyclones: [[Hurricane Iris (1995)|Tropical Storm Iris]] on 28 August caused minor damages; [[Hurricane Luis]] on 5 September caused moderate damages in north coast of Grande-Terre; [[Hurricane Marilyn]] on 15 September caused moderate damages in Basse-Terre. * On 20 September 1998, [[Hurricane Georges]] pounded the islands, decimated the banana crops at nearly 100%.
== Statistics == ; Location: : [[Caribbean]], [[island]]s in the eastern [[Caribbean Sea]], southeast of [[Cuba]] and [[Hispaniola]]. ; [[Geographic coordinates]]: : {{Coord|16|15|N|61|35|W|type:country}} ; Map references: : [[Central America]] and the Caribbean ; Area: :* Total: {{convert|abbr=on|1,628|km2|sqmi|0}} :* Land: {{convert|abbr=on|1,554|km2|sqmi|0}} :* Water: {{convert|abbr=on|74|km2|sqmi|0}} :* Note: Guadeloupe department is composed of six inhabited islands: the main islands which formed Guadeloupe island: [[Basse-Terre Island]] on the west and [[Grande-Terre]] on the east, and the nearby smaller islands : [[Marie-Galante]], [[La Desirade]], [[Iles des Saintes]] (Terre-de-Haut island and Terre-de-Bas island). ; Area – comparative: : 10 times the size of Washington, DC ; Coastline: : {{convert|abbr=on|306|km|mi|0}} ; Maritime claims: :* Exclusive economic zone: {{convert|abbr=on|200|nmi|km mi|1|lk=in}} :* Territorial sea: {{convert|abbr=on|12|nmi|km mi|1}} ; Climate: : Tropical tempered by trade winds; moderately high humidity ; Terrain: : Basse-Terre is volcanic in origin with interior mountains; Grande-Terre is low limestone formation; most of the seven other islands are volcanic in origin ; Elevation extremes: :* Lowest point: Caribbean Sea 0 m :* Highest point: [[La Grande Soufrière]] - {{convert|abbr=on|1,467|m|ft|0}} ; Natural resources: : Cultivable land, beaches and climate that foster tourism ; Land use: :* Arable land: 14% :* Permanent crops: 4% :* Permanent pastures: 14% :* Forests and woodland: 39% :* Other: 29% (1993 est.) ; Irrigated land: : 30 km<sup>2</sup> or 12 sq mi (1993 est.) ; Natural hazards: : Hurricanes (June to October); [[La Grande Soufrière]] is an active volcano ; Environment – current issues: : NA
