{{for|the Olympic sailor|Henri Gauthier (sailor)}}
'''Henri Louis Marie Alexandre Gauthier''' (19 September 1877 – 1950<ref name="DawsonUphill1972">{{cite book |last1=Dawson |first1=Warren Royal |last2=Uphill |first2=Eric Parrington |title=Who was who in Egyptology … |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xHVSVbY95S8C |accessdate=21 October 2012 |date=December 1972 |publisher=Egypt Exploration Society |page=114}}</ref>) was a French [[Egyptologist]] and geographer. In 1903 he entered the [[French Institute of Oriental Archaeology of Cairo]]. He made extensive excavations at [[Dra Abu el-Naga]] and [[El Qattah]] (1904),<ref name="DawsonUphill1972" /> and devoted himself to work on both historical and geographical<ref name="Bernal2001">{{cite book |last=Bernal |first=Martin |title=Black Athena Writes Back: Martin Bernal Responds to His Critics |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=UJ94DaPauu8C&pg=PA159 |accessdate=21 October 2012 |date=30 August 2001 |publisher=Duke University Press |isbn=978-0-8223-2717-2 |page=159}}</ref> issues of Ancient Egypt. In 1909 he was part of a French team which discovered [[Huni#Cultic step pyramids|Huni's Pyramid]] in [[Elephantine]], and discovered a large [[granite]] conical object with an inscription revealing the name of the pharaoh [[Huni]] of the [[Third dynasty of Egypt|3rd dynasty]] of the [[Old Kingdom of Egypt|Old Kingdom]].<ref name="Verner2003">{{cite book |last=Verner |first=Miroslav |title=The pyramids: their archaeology and history |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=nIFR5PiplHAC |accessdate=21 October 2012 |date=5 December 2003 |publisher=Atlantic |isbn=978-1-84354-171-4 |page=172}}</ref>  Gauthier worked with [[Gaston Maspero]]<ref name="MaspéroGauthier1939">{{cite book |last1=Maspéro |first1=Gaston |last2=Gauthier |first2=Henri |title=Sarcophages des époques persane et ptolémaïque |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=6XaBbwAACAAJ |accessdate=21 October 2012 |year=1939 |publisher=Inst. Français d'Archéologie Orientale}}</ref> who asked him to copy the inscriptions of the [[Nubia]]n temples of [[Amada]], [[Kalabsha]] and [[Wadi Seboua]].

